A similar pattern appeared at FEMA. More than 180 employees signed what became known as the \'93Katrina Declaration,\'94 a letter to Congress warning that one\uc0\u8209 third of the agency\'92s full\u8209 time staff had left that year, eroding its capacity to respond to disasters. They described mismanagement and inexperience at the top and drew explicit parallels to the failures of Hurricane Katrina. Shortly after the letter became public, about 30 signatories were placed on administrative leave. The message to the remaining staff was clear. Speaking candidly about risk and competence could cost them their jobs. The combination of internal warnings and swift retaliation showed how whistleblowers were being punished rather than protected, and how the government\'92s ability to respond to real emergencies was being sacrificed to preserve the image of control.\
\
The administration\'92s reach into independent economic institutions also deepened. Trump announced that the United States now owned a 10% stake in Intel, a major semiconductor firm, after personally demanding the equity in a meeting with the company\'92s CEO. The deal was presented as costing taxpayers nothing, but critics across the political spectrum saw it as a step toward state ownership of private firms without clear legal or policy frameworks. Reports suggested that similar stakes were being considered in other companies with large government contracts. At the same time, the Federal Housing Finance Agency, led by Bill Pulte, used detailed mortgage data to investigate political opponents, including Lisa Cook. The same week, Trump threatened and then attempted to fire Cook, the first Black woman to serve as a Federal Reserve governor, over unproven mortgage\uc0\u8209 fraud allegations. Cook insisted that the president lacked authority to remove her without cause and vowed to fight in court. The combined effect of these moves was to blur the line between public regulation and private leverage, turning key economic and housing agencies into instruments of patronage and intimidation.\
