Labor policy was reshaped in ways that stripped protections from millions of workers. Trump issued an executive order further excluding certain federal agencies and subdivisions from the Federal Labor\uc0\u8209 Management Relations Program, citing national security to remove their employees from standard collective bargaining rights. More sweeping still were a set of proposals and actions that targeted wages and overtime. The administration cut the minimum wage for federal contractors from $17.75 to $13.30 an hour. It rescinded a minimum wage requirement for disabled workers, allowing subminimum pay to return in settings where advocates had fought for equal standards. A proposed rule would eliminate federal minimum wage and overtime protections for 3.7 million childcare and home care workers, some of the lowest\u8209 paid and most essential workers in the country. These changes were not isolated technical adjustments. Together they amounted to what observers called the largest single act of union busting in U.S. history, aimed at federal workers, contractors, disabled employees, and care workers alike.\
