The economic burden of the administration\'92s trade policy fell heavily on ordinary consumers and small businesses. Trump ended the de minimis tariff exemption for packages valued under $800, a rule that had allowed low\uc0\u8209 value imports to enter the country without duties. Postal services in nearly 30 countries suspended deliveries to the United States as they scrambled to adjust, and analysts estimated that the change could add up to $13 billion in costs and delays. The White House justified the move as protecting American manufacturers and addressing national security concerns. In practice, it raised prices and disrupted supply chains for small retailers and lower\u8209 income consumers who relied on affordable imports. The same week, Trump threatened tariffs on countries that imposed digital services taxes, escalating trade tensions with allies. These decisions, combined with the Intel stake and talk of broader nationalization, pointed toward an economic order where presidential preferences, not stable rules, determined who prospered and who paid.\
