By the close of Week 32, the Democracy Clock remained at 8:07 p.m. in public view, but the internal advance of half a minute mattered. It marked a week in which the moral floor sagged further under the weight of emergency rule, politicized law, and stratified citizenship. Executive power operated with fewer effective checks, not because the Constitution had been rewritten, but because norms of restraint, truthfulness, and stewardship were treated as optional. Law was increasingly something to be aimed, not obeyed. Labor protections were not merely trimmed but attacked at scale, leaving millions more workers exposed and dependent. Expert agencies like the CDC and FEMA were hollowed out, their leaders purged or cowed, even as their formal procedures continued. Courts and governors showed that resistance was still possible, and civil society refused to be silent. But the balance of power shifted another notch toward a system where fear, not law, set the boundaries of public life. That is why the clock\'92s hand, though still on the same minute mark, edged closer to night.\
